 in order to ensure order and stability. Suggesting that all concepts of modern political thought are secularized theological concepts, Schmitt concludes Political Theology with a critique of liberalism and its attempt to depoliticize political thought by avoiding fundamental political decisions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 0aPolitical science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aSchwab, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwab, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStrong, Tracy B.1 aStrong, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226738901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226738901.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles